description: Originally borrowed from Latin inceptus, past participle of incipio. The term is marked "obsolete" in the first edition of the OED (1905); newer usage is a back-formation from inception.

verbs.description: incept (third-person singular simple present incepts, present participle incepting, simple past and past participle incepted)

entries.meaning: (UK) To be accepted to the Master of Arts degree at Oxford or Cambridge University.

(transitive) To put an idea into a person's mind so deeply that they believe it was their own. Inspired by the movie Inception (2010) and used by Mark Zuckerberg & Yuval Noah Harari in Conversation at 01:23:00.
examples: Is the idea really yours? Or was it incepted into your mind by your friend?
